                          "name": "b2text",
                          "fill": "#D4D4D8",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "Photosynthesis begins when chlorophyll absorbs light energy. This energy is used to split water molecules (H2O) into hydrogen and oxygen. The oxygen is released as a byproduct, while the hydrogen ions are used to generate ATP and NADPH.\n\nThese energy carriers then power the Calvin cycle, where carbon dioxide is converted into glucose.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.65,
                          "fontFamily": "Inter",
                          "fontSize": 14,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
